explanation:
To determine whether any code in OS_DirectoryRead is unreachable you must know the control-flow semantics and side effects of macros, function calls, constants and types used by the function:

- OS_CHECK_POINTER: This macro is invoked at the top of the function and can contain control-flow (e.g. return, goto, or call to an abort routine). Its definition is required to know whether the remainder of the function can be skipped/unreachable when dirent is NULL.

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: The if-statement guarding the core block depends entirely on this call's result and any side effects (e.g. early-exit, longjmp, or modifying the token). Its contract and possible return values determine reachability of the inside block and the subsequent OS_ObjectIdRelease call.

- OS_SUCCESS: The if condition compares return_code to this constant. The exact value is needed to interpret OS_ObjectIdGetById results and to decide which branches are possible.

- OS_DirRead_Impl: Called inside the guarded block; if this implementation can perform non-local control transfers (abort/longjmp/noreturn) it could make code after it (including OS_ObjectIdRelease) unreachable. Its prototype and behavior are therefore needed.

- OS_ObjectIdRelease: Called inside the guarded block to release the token. If this function can transfer control (noreturn) or has preconditions on token validity, that affects whether subsequent code is reachable or whether the call itself might be unreachable in some scenarios.

- OS_LOCK_MODE_GLOBAL and LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: These macros/constants are passed into OS_ObjectIdGetById; their definitions may affect the behavior of OS_ObjectIdGetById (e.g. selecting transactional paths) and thus affect which branches are possible.

- OS_object_token_t: The token variable type is used by ObjectIdGetById/Release; its size/initialization/validity rules may influence whether Release is required or reachable and whether ObjectIdGetById can legitimately succeed.

- osal_id_t: The dir_id parameter type; understanding its valid value ranges or special values (e.g. invalid id sentinel) can influence whether ObjectIdGetById can return OS_SUCCESS and thus whether the guarded block is reachable.

- os_dirent_t: The pointer checked by OS_CHECK_POINTER; its definition may be referenced by the macro (alignment/size) or by callees and can affect whether the initial check causes an early return.

- OS_printf: Present in the static call graph and commonly used by checking macros or error paths; if any of the above macros/functions call OS_printf and then return/abort, that affects reachability. Include to inspect side-effects used by macros/error handling.

- int32: The return type/typedef used by the function and return_code variable; knowing whether this is a normal signed int typedef is necessary to interpret return values/comparisons consistently.

Collectively these symbols define the only control-flow and noreturn/early-exit behavior visible from OS_DirectoryRead. Inspecting their definitions lets the next analyzer determine if any lines/statements in OS_DirectoryRead are impossible to reach (i.e. violate the "no unreachable code" MISRA requirement).
